	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Sat Jan 26, 2013 4:48 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: YPbPr ouput mod for SNES consoles</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Ziggy587 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">1): AC or DC coupled output ? <br /><br />2): Best way to kill the voltage on the Pr and Pb lines without effecting the image quality?</div>IMO, these are same question.<br /><br />The easiest is AC coupled. Use a highpass filter with corner frequency &lt; 1.6kHz (1/10th of horizontal line frequency). Assuming the TV has a 75Ω input impedance, this would be ⅟(2·π·75Ω·1.6kHz)=1.3µF. So a 1µF decoupling capacitor would be pretty close, and a little larger would be a little better.<br /><br />Adding a DC offset (for DC coupling) will require a different schematic, and will probably require a different kind of opamp, but a &quot;difference amplifier&quot; would be how I would do that.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Ziggy587</b> [ Sat Jan 26, 2013 8:25 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: YPbPr ouput mod for SNES consoles</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">AaronE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What I'm planning to do is pull the signals from pins 1 and 24, run them through a recreated RC circuit that is a copy of the ones on the board, and then follow the schematics on gamex for the N64 mod.</div><br /><br />Yes, I'm pretty much planning on doing the same thing. Two things though: One, when I took Pr and Pb from the input pins (after the RC circuit) I also had a 1k resistor to ground at the input of the amp. So if you recreate that RC circuit, you will have to tack on a 1k resistor to ground at the end of it. IIRC, the voltage is slightly higher on one of the lines, so you might not need that 1k resistor on both lines. And two, if you're using a slightly newer version of the amp from the N64 mod on GameSX, than you might wanna read through the datasheet for it just to make sure anything vital didn't change (like capacitor or resistor values, adding or omitting parts). <br /><br />The only other thing, I've noticed that I get different voltages depending on whether the console is plugged into a TV or not. So you'll want to consider that when testing.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">IMO, these are same question.</div><br /><br />Sorry, let me clarify what I meant with #2. I meant what is he best way to kill the voltage <em>before</em> the amp. Right now, the two schematics I've posted above are the only things I have to try.<br /><br />So, AC coupled output is the way to go? That's what I suspected. Thanks!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


