	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">AaronE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What I'm planning to do is pull the signals from pins 1 and 24, run them through a recreated RC circuit that is a copy of the ones on the board, and then follow the schematics on gamex for the N64 mod.</div><br /><br />So, I was just checking some things out. I was looking at the schematic for the N64 RGB mod with the NJM2267 and noticed something comparing it to the datasheet. <br /><br /><a href="http://www.gamesx.com/wiki/doku.php?id=av:n64rgb-amp" class="postlink">N64 RGB mod from GameSX</a>:<br /><img src="http://www.gamesx.com/wiki/lib/exe/fetch.php?cache=&amp;media=av:n64rgb.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />From NJM2267 datasheet:<br /><img src="http://i59.photobucket.com/albums/g295/Ziggy587/NJM2267_zpsab68bdff.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />Take a look at the outputs. See how in the data sheet it shows &quot;Vout1&quot; then &quot;Vout1 (6dB)&quot;? Now if you look at the outputs in the schematic from the GameSX mod, there's just a series 75Ohm resistor (and no resistor to ground). So I'm just wondering what the deal is. The person that created the N64 schematic, why didn't he use the 75Ohm resistor to ground as shown in the datasheet? And also, if we WANT the 6dB gain, then what do we do? Omit the two 75Ohm resistors?<br /><br />AaronE, I realize you said you're using the newer NJM2268, but I believe the datasheet for it shows the same thing. <br /><br />My parts came in. I have the NJM2267 and the THS7314, and a whole mess of capacitors and resistors. I'll post my results as soon as I get the chance to mess with it all.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
